<h2 id="org9b42a74"><span class="section-number-2">24</span> 23 Nightfall 1 - Death</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-24">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>"Ash that could be touched, unlike his soul." Why can one be touched and not the other?</li>
<li>"Bruno was burned." Who is Bruno</li>
<li>In this paragraph can you see any similarity to Hamlet? To be or not to be &#x2026;</li>
<li>How does Galileo relate death and consciousness? Is this consistent with the integrated information account? Is it testable?</li>
<li>From the evidence in this chapter do you believe that Tononi is a physicalist? How to accomodate his statement that: "&#x2026;consciousness did not reduce to matter&#x2026;But consciousness did rely on matter"?</li>
<li>What is a demiurge?</li>
<li>If consciousness is in principle a mechanical relation between parts, would it have to end with death? Could you sustain it? Recreate it? Duplicate it?</li>
<li>On the other hand if you equate consciousness with Phi, doesn't consciousness "die" with each changing shape?</li>
<li>Is death in fact relevant for physicalist theories, or more a selfish preoccupation?</li>
</ul>
